Sponsor ljmf00

Hi, I'm Luís Ferreira, an open source developer from Portugal.

I'm a 21 years old student passionate about computers, highly motivated, and interested in the Free Software movement and Open Source projects. I'm interested in developing compilers and parsers and I also like to develop tooling and integrate them. I also like to develop correct and secure distributed back-end infrastructures with low-level power and some decentralization in mind. I'm mostly proficient in D, C, and C++.

Over time, I've been contributed to several open source projects including D programming language, LLVM, mesonbuild, Linux Kernel, GCC, and many others... I also maintain some packages on Arch Linux AUR repository. You can check most of my open source work here or visit my projects page on my personal website, here.

  • 10/28/22, 3:44 PM
    Commented on #14600 changelog: Check filenames match expected format in pre_commit pipeline. from dlang/dmd

    This does make sense to me, but not the way it is currently implemented. The intention of pre-commit is to prevent people from committing non-compliant things like files, and hang the git commit via the git pre-commit hook. The action is here just to double-check or to run the pre-commit for people who don't have it set up, but if this was on the pre-commit config, people that have this setup won't be able to commit such changes.

    The idea is to avoid hanging with trivial changes in the review process. There's other rudimentary scripts around the posix.mak and other files to do syntax checking with grep, that chould be easily changed to pre-commit and would have a way better experience for everyone, like, instead of hanging Buildkite with style issues, these issues could be checked by pre-commit.

    I can change this when I have time.

  • 10/28/22, 2:11 PM
    Commented on #14600 changelog: Check filenames match expected format in pre_commit pipeline. from dlang/dmd

    pre-commit looks like a deprecated action to me.

    It's a complicated story. Basically, it is deprecated because there's a pre-commit Github application and the dev considers it deprecated as it can lead to insecure usage (if used with the push permission when auto-fix is enabled). There are other reasons to be deprecated, as pre-commit is backed by a company (PRE-COMMIT CI, LLC) and there might be interest in not maintaining the action. We don't use push permissions to auto-fix changes, so it is fine to use it.

    The community wants to maintain the action, but the maintainer is a bit arrogant, so suggesting upstream changes lead to rejection, issue blocking, or even user blocking (Several issues demonstrating that pre-commit/pre-commi#1982 (comment) , pre-commit/actio#148). It is kind of unfortunate, but I'm blocked by him due to forking his project, see the last referenced issue. I'm maintaining a work-in-progress fork of the action (https://github.com/before-commit/run-action), but currently, the action we are using is going to indefinitely work with updated pre-commit, as it uses pip to download the package. I never switched to the forked action as I don't have enough time to make it stable with all the features I want to add.

  • 10/28/22, 1:43 PM
    Commented on #14600 changelog: Check filenames match expected format in pre_commit pipeline. from dlang/dmd

    Don't add this check to Github workflows. This way pre-commit is not useful when installed locally. You can add it properly to pre-commit. pre-commit is very extensible, with scripts, regex and other languages. See https://pre-commit.com/index.html#new-hooks . The best portable way is to write Python scripting if what you want to achieve is not possible with e.g. fail hook type, with matching regex files. You have an example of scripts from the community for a similar thing you want to do, see https://github.com/Sceptre/sceptrelint .

    Commented on #8598 Add isAllocator from dlang/phobos

    Why are we adding a public symbol to Phobos without tagging me? Also, what is this for?

    I think this is really not the best approach to ask for clarifications.

    What would your suggestion be?

    It's all related to governance. I would say that the necessity of tagging you on every Phobos addition is not formally a requirement, even though we know its a good rule of thumb to do so. I just think you can express that clarification in other non-authoritative/soft ways. Anyway, to avoid these situation we should have a more defined governance procedures to solve ambiguities. Maybe we should have more than X approvals on simple additions such as this one and give Y amount of time before merging.
